transport), while uncovered pairs retain their original cost. Non-negativity
is enforced by the \eqn{\max(\cdot, 0)} clamp.

\strong{Clamp behaviour at large \code{rho_anchor}.} When the anchor bonus exceeds
\eqn{C_{kl}}, the effective cost is clamped to zero. All such pairs then
have identical effective cost and the transport mass among them is determined
by entropic regularisation alone rather than by relative anchor counts.
The clamp is required to keep costs non-negative; at very large \code{rho_anchor}
the plan for anchor-covered pairs becomes more entropic, not more
concentrated. A practical upper bound is \code{rho_anchor * max(A) / n_anchors <= 1}, i.e., even the most-supported pair reduces cost by at most one
median-distance unit.

\strong{Fallback for uncovered nodes.} Query nodes with no anchor samples retain
their original pairwise costs, so the transport plan for those nodes is
determined entirely by the OT objective — the same as \code{\link[=somalign_fit]{somalign_fit()}}.
Inspect \verb{$anchors$coverage_fraction} to see what fraction of query nodes
had at least one anchor pair.

